                          <h3 class="highlight header-colorize text-uppercase mb-4"><a href="https://www.marshall.edu/academics/programs/creative-writing-ba/">Creative Writing, B.A.</a></h3>
                              <p class="mb-4 size-18">Students who choose to study Creative Writing at Marshall University, Huntington, WV, do so for a variety of reasons. For some, it’s the opportunity to pursue a lifelong passion. They love to write—and want to continue to get better at it. For others, a class in Creative Writing, which may have been an elective course, quickly turns into something more serious—and leads to becoming their major.</p>
                                <p class="mb-4 size-18">The Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree in Creative Writing offers a comprehensive learning experience for aspiring writers. Creative Writing majors develop their skills in fiction, poetry and creative nonfiction; they have opportunities to study with talented writers on Marshall’s faculty; and they get to share their own writing in workshops with other writers.</p>
                                  <p class="mb-4 size-18">Like other bachelor’s degrees in Marshall’s English Department, a Creative Writing degree helps strengthen skills in communication, analysis and critical thinking. These are skills that are valuable for a career in writing—and important to professional work across a wide range of fields.</p>
                                  <p class="mb-4 size-18">The Creative Writing program at Marshall has served as an important steppingstone for emerging writers to be recognized and published. Over the past three years, several Creative Writing alumni, including Nora Shalaway Carpenter, Rajia Hassib, Lydia Cyrus and others, have won prestigious writing awards and published acclaimed novels, poetry and prose.</p>
                                  <p class="mb-4 size-18">In 2021, a Creative Writing major, RaJon Staunton, received Honorable Mention in the Intro Journals Project writing competition of the Association of Writers and Writing Programs. This is the first time a Marshall University student has ever placed in this prestigious national competition.</p>
                          <h4 class="header-colorize">Why Study Creative Writing at Marshall?</h4>
                          <p class="mb-4 size-18">The Creative Writing bachelor’s program is flexible, enabling majors to pursue a wide range of interests. Creative Writing courses encourage students to think differently, expand on and augment many ideas, and explore all fields, not just focus on literature.</p>
                          <h4>Talented Faculty</h4>
                          <p class="mb-4 size-18">Creative Writing courses aim to hone not just students’ writing but also their thinking, ensuring that majors develop a skillset that’s vital to all types of lifetime work. The faculty and staff in the Creative Writing Program are dedicated to helping students discover and develop their talents. Their commitment is to prepare each student for a successful professional life as well as for an invaluable way of thinking—about everything.</p>
                          <h4>Vital Connections</h4>
                          <p class="mb-4 size-18">Beyond coursework, Creative Writing majors have opportunities to meet nationally renowned authors through Marshall’s A.E. Stringer Visiting Writers Series. Recent authors who have participated include: Kiese Laymon, Eula Biss, Jayne Anne Phillips, Afaa Michael Weaver, Hanif Abdurraqib and many more.</p>
                          <p class="mb-4 size-18">The Creative Writing program at Marshall also sponsors Et Cetera, a student-edited literary journal, published annually since 1953. Et Cetera provides opportunities for Creative Writing majors to be published, along with offering hands-on experience for student editors.</p>
                          <h4>Flexible Format</h4>
                          <p class="mb-4 size-18">Creative Writing majors can complete their bachelor’s degree on a traditional, four-year schedule (fall and spring semesters only, full-time) on Marshall’s Huntington campus. Students who want to get into the workforce sooner (and minimize student loan debt) can choose the Accelerated Creative Writing degree program by taking classes in summers as well as in fall and spring semesters to complete the degree in three years.</p>
